<!-- 1: CONTEXT -->
<!-- SECTION: Context First: Read Before Any Rule -->
<section id="context" class="c1">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">1</span>Context First: Read Before Any Rule</h2>
  <p>Read the conversation. Just try to understand. We look at the grammar after.</p>

  <div class="realia">
    <span class="doc-tag">First Day of Class</span>
    <div class="chat">
      <div class="bubble teacher"><div class="name">Sam (teacher)</div>Hello! Welcome! What's your name?</div>
      <div class="bubble right"><div class="name">Elena</div>Hello! <span class="highlight">I'm</span> Elena.</div>
      <div class="bubble teacher"><div class="name">Sam</div>Nice to meet you, Elena. Where <span class="highlight">are you</span> from?</div>
      <div class="bubble right"><div class="name">Elena</div><span class="highlight">I'm</span> from Poland. <span class="highlight">I'm</span> Polish.</div>
      <div class="bubble teacher"><div class="name">Sam</div>Great! And you?</div>
      <div class="bubble left"><div class="name">Diego</div>Hi! <span class="highlight">I'm</span> Diego. <span class="highlight">I'm</span> from Mexico. <span class="highlight">I'm</span> Mexican.</div>
      <div class="bubble teacher"><div class="name">Sam</div>Welcome, Diego! How <span class="highlight">are you</span> today?</div>
      <div class="bubble left"><div class="name">Diego</div><span class="highlight">I'm</span> fine, thanks. A little tired!</div>
      <div class="bubble right"><div class="name">Elena</div>Me too! <span class="highlight2">I've got</span> three children, so <span class="highlight">I'm</span> always tired! 😊</div>
      <div class="bubble left"><div class="name">Diego</div>Ha! <span class="highlight2">I've got</span> a big family too. <span class="highlight2">I've got</span> two brothers and one sister.</div>
      <div class="bubble teacher"><div class="name">Sam</div>Lovely! OK everyone, open your books to page one!</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p><em>Notice:</em> Elena and Diego use "I'm" (I am) a lot to talk about their name, country, and feelings. They also use "I've got" to talk about family.</p>
</section>

<!-- 2: NOTICE -->
<!-- SECTION: Notice the Language (Before Any Rule) -->
<section id="notice" class="c2">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">2</span>Notice the Language (Before Any Rule)</h2>
  <p>You've just read how Elena and Diego introduced themselves on their first day. Before we name any grammar rules, let's look closely at the exact words they used — noticing the pattern yourself makes the rule much easier to remember later.</p>
  <p>Look again at the highlighted words in Sam, Elena and Diego's conversation. Talk to a partner about these questions.</p>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q1.</b> Find every "I'm" in the conversation. "I'm" is short for two words. Which two words?</div>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q2.</b> Sam asks "How are you?" and "Where are you from?" Which word — "am", "is", or "are" — goes with "you"?</div>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q3.</b> Find "I've got three children" and "I've got two brothers". What do you think "I've got" means?</div>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q4.</b> Elena is a woman's name, and Diego is a man's name. In the conversation, do we ever use "he" or "she"? Why do you think not, yet?</div>
  <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--ink-soft);">Talk about your answers before you go to Section 3.</p>
</section>

<!-- 3: GRAMMAR -->
<!-- SECTION: Grammar Focus -->
<section id="grammar" class="c3">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">3</span>Grammar Focus</h2>
  <p>You noticed that Elena and Diego both said <b>"I'm..."</b>, and that Sam asked <b>"Are you...?"</b> Now let's turn those patterns into clear rules — ones you can use to talk about yourself, or anyone else, not just Elena and Diego.</p>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.1 — The Verb "To Be"</h3>
  <p>"To be" is the most important verb in English. It changes depending on who we are talking about.</p>

  <div class="tl-diagram">
    <div class="tl-diagram-title">Am, is, or are?</div>
    <svg viewBox="0 0 660 190" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
      <rect x="20" y="30" width="190" height="130" rx="12" fill="#d9ede7"/>
      <text x="115" y="60" font-size="30" text-anchor="middle">🙋</text>
      <text x="115" y="90" font-size="18" fill="#2e7d6b" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">AM</text>
      <text x="115" y="112" font-size="13" fill="#26312e" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">I am</text>
      <text x="115" y="132" font-size="12" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">(I'm)</text>

      <rect x="235" y="30" width="190" height="130" rx="12" fill="#fbe8d3"/>
      <text x="330" y="60" font-size="30" text-anchor="middle">🧑🤝🧑</text>
      <text x="330" y="90" font-size="18" fill="#e08e45" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">ARE</text>
      <text x="330" y="112" font-size="13" fill="#26312e" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">you / we / they are</text>
      <text x="330" y="132" font-size="12" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">(you're / we're / they're)</text>

      <rect x="450" y="30" width="190" height="130" rx="12" fill="#dcebf5"/>
      <text x="545" y="60" font-size="30" text-anchor="middle">🙂</text>
      <text x="545" y="90" font-size="18" fill="#3e7cb1" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">IS</text>
      <text x="545" y="112" font-size="13" fill="#26312e" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">he / she / it is</text>
      <text x="545" y="132" font-size="12" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">(he's / she's / it's)</text>
    </svg>
    <div class="tl-caption">"I am Elena." "You are Diego." "She is happy." "We are students."</div>
  </div>

  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Positive</th><th>Negative</th><th>Question</th></tr>
    <tr><td>I <b>am</b> (I'm) tired.</td><td>I <b>am not</b> (I'm not) tired.</td><td><b>Am I</b> late?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>You <b>are</b> (you're) happy.</td><td>You <b>aren't</b> happy.</td><td><b>Are you</b> happy?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>She <b>is</b> (she's) from Spain.</td><td>She <b>isn't</b> from Spain.</td><td><b>Is she</b> from Spain?</td></tr>
  </table></div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Do we say "I is" or "I am"?</b> <span>I am.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Do we say "you is" or "you are"?</b> <span>You are.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Do we say "she are" or "she is"?</b> <span>She is.</span></div>
  </div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.2 — Have Got</h3>
  <p>Elena and Diego didn't only talk about names and countries — they also talked about their families: "I've got three children," "I've got two brothers." We use "have got" to talk about family, possessions, and things we have.</p>

  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Subject</th><th>Form</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td>I / you / we / they</td><td><b>'ve got</b></td><td>I<b>'ve got</b> three children.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>he / she / it</td><td><b>'s got</b></td><td>She<b>'s got</b> two brothers.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>negative</td><td><b>haven't/hasn't got</b></td><td>I <b>haven't got</b> a sister.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>question</td><td><b>Have/Has...got?</b></td><td><b>Have you got</b> children?</td></tr>
  </table></div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Do we say "I's got" or "I've got"?</b> <span>I've got.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Do we say "he've got" or "he's got"?</b> <span>He's got.</span></div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 4: CLASSROOM LANGUAGE -->
<!-- SECTION: Classroom Language -->
<section id="classroom" class="c4">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">4</span>Classroom Language</h2>
  <p>Right at the end of the conversation, Sam said "open your books to page one!" That's just one of many short instructions your teacher will use every single class. Let's learn to recognise the most common ones now, so nothing catches you by surprise.</p>
  <div class="classroom-grid">
