<!-- 1: CONTEXT -->
<!-- SECTION: Context First: Read Before Any Rule -->
<section id="context" class="c1">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">1</span>Context First: Read Before Any Rule</h2>
  <p>Read the class conversation. Just try to understand. We look at the grammar after.</p>

  <div class="realia">
    <span class="doc-tag">Class Conversation</span>
    <div class="chat">
      <div class="bubble teacher"><div class="name">Sam</div>OK, everyone! What's your job?</div>
      <div class="bubble right"><div class="name">Elena</div>I'm <span class="highlight">a</span> nurse. It's hard work, <span class="highlight3">but</span> I love it.</div>
      <div class="bubble left"><div class="name">Diego</div>I'm <span class="highlight">a</span> chef! I'm <span class="highlight3">and</span>... wait — I'm tired <span class="highlight3">and</span> happy today, all at once!</div>
      <div class="bubble teacher"><div class="name">Sam</div>Ha! And you, Yuki?</div>
      <div class="bubble left"><div class="name">Yuki</div>Hi! I'm <span class="highlight">an</span> engineer. I'm <span class="highlight2">a hard-working</span> engineer!</div>
      <div class="bubble right"><div class="name">Elena</div>Nice! Diego, are you <span class="highlight">a</span> chef <span class="highlight3">or</span> <span class="highlight">a</span> waiter?</div>
      <div class="bubble left"><div class="name">Diego</div>I'm <span class="highlight">a</span> chef! I'm <span class="highlight2">a happy</span> chef, <span class="highlight3">but</span> I'm <span class="highlight2">a busy</span> chef too.</div>
      <div class="bubble teacher"><div class="name">Sam</div>Great! Now, turn to your partner <span class="highlight3">and</span> ask about their job.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p><em>Notice:</em> Elena, Diego and Yuki use "a" and "an" before job words. They also put describing words like "hard-working", "happy" and "busy" before the job word. Small words like "and", "but" and "or" connect their ideas.</p>
</section>

<!-- 2: NOTICE -->
<!-- SECTION: Notice the Language (Before Any Rule) -->
<section id="notice" class="c2">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">2</span>Notice the Language (Before Any Rule)</h2>
  <p>You've just read how Elena, Diego and Yuki talked about their jobs. Before we name any grammar rules, let's look closely at the exact words they used — this will make the rules much easier to understand.</p>
  <p>Look again at the highlighted words. Talk to a partner about these questions.</p>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q1.</b> Find "a nurse", "a chef" and "an engineer". Why does "engineer" use "an" instead of "a"? Listen to the first sound.</div>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q2.</b> Look at "a hard-working engineer" and "a happy chef". Does the describing word (hard-working, happy) come before or after the job word?</div>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q3.</b> Find "tired and happy", "hard work, but I love it", and "a chef or a waiter". Which word joins two similar ideas? Which word shows a difference? Which word shows a choice?</div>
  <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--ink-soft);">Talk about your answers before you go to Section 3.</p>
</section>

<!-- 3: GRAMMAR -->
<!-- SECTION: Grammar Focus -->
<section id="grammar" class="c3">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">3</span>Grammar Focus</h2>
  <p>You noticed that Yuki said "an engineer" while Elena said "a nurse" — and that describing words like "happy" and "hard-working" came right before the job. Now let's turn those patterns into clear rules you can use for any job, not just Elena's, Diego's or Yuki's.</p>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.1 — A or An?</h3>
  <p>We use "a" before a consonant <b>sound</b>, and "an" before a vowel <b>sound</b> (a, e, i, o, u).</p>

  <div class="tl-diagram">
    <div class="tl-diagram-title">A or an? Listen to the first sound</div>
    <svg viewBox="0 0 640 170" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
      <rect x="30" y="30" width="270" height="110" rx="12" fill="#d9ede7"/>
      <text x="165" y="60" font-size="20" fill="#2e7d6b" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">A</text>
      <text x="165" y="85" font-size="13" fill="#26312e" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">a nurse, a chef,</text>
      <text x="165" y="105" font-size="13" fill="#26312e" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">a teacher, a doctor</text>
      <text x="165" y="127" font-size="11.5" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" font-style="italic" text-anchor="middle">consonant sound first</text>

      <rect x="340" y="30" width="270" height="110" rx="12" fill="#fbe8d3"/>
      <text x="475" y="60" font-size="20" fill="#e08e45" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">AN</text>
      <text x="475" y="85" font-size="13" fill="#26312e" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">an engineer, an artist,</text>
      <text x="475" y="105" font-size="13" fill="#26312e" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">an actor, an office</text>
      <text x="475" y="127" font-size="11.5" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" font-style="italic" text-anchor="middle">vowel sound first (a,e,i,o,u)</text>
    </svg>
    <div class="tl-caption">"An" is easier to say before a vowel sound — try saying "a engineer" out loud, it's difficult!</div>
  </div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Do we say "a engineer" or "an engineer"?</b> <span>An engineer.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Do we say "a nurse" or "an nurse"?</b> <span>A nurse.</span></div>
  </div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.2 — Adjectives with Nouns</h3>
  <p>Yuki didn't just say "an engineer" — she said "a hard-working engineer." A describing word (adjective) goes <b>before</b> the noun it describes.</p>
  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Adjective + Noun</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td>happy + chef</td><td>a <b>happy</b> chef</td></tr>
    <tr><td>hard-working + engineer</td><td>a <b>hard-working</b> engineer</td></tr>
    <tr><td>busy + nurse</td><td>a <b>busy</b> nurse</td></tr>
  </table></div>
  <div class="error-box">
    <h4>⚠️ Word Order Matters!</h4>
    <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
      <tr><th>❌ Incorrect</th><th>✅ Correct</th></tr>
      <tr><td>a chef happy</td><td>a <b>happy</b> chef</td></tr>
      <tr><td>an engineer hard-working</td><td>a <b>hard-working</b> engineer</td></tr>
    </table></div>
  </div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Does the adjective go before or after the noun?</b> <span>Before.</span></div>
  </div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.3 — And, But, Or</h3>
  <p>Diego said he was "tired <b>and</b> happy," Elena said her job was hard, "<b>but</b>" she loves it, and she asked Diego if he was a chef "<b>or</b>" a waiter. These three small words connect ideas in very different ways.</p>
  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Word</th><th>Job</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td><b>and</b></td><td>adds two similar ideas</td><td>I'm tired <b>and</b> happy.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>but</b></td><td>shows a difference/contrast</td><td>It's hard work, <b>but</b> I love it.</td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>or</b></td><td>shows a choice</td><td>Are you a chef <b>or</b> a waiter?</td></tr>
  </table></div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Which word shows a choice between two things?</b> <span>Or.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Which word shows a difference or a surprise?</b> <span>But.</span></div>
  </div>
</section>

