<!-- 6: ERROR CLINIC -->
<!-- SECTION: Error Clinic -->
<section id="errorclinic" class="c6">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">6</span>Error Clinic</h2>
  <p>Even careful learners mix up "a/an" and word order when they're new to English. Here are five sentences a student might write — read each one. Some have mistakes — fix them. <b>One sentence is already correct — do not "fix" it if it isn't broken.</b></p>
  <div class="box" style="padding:16px 20px;">
    <ol style="font-size:14.5px;">
      <li>"I'm a engineer." <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content">Incorrect — "engineer" starts with a vowel sound: "I'm <b>an</b> engineer."</div></li>
      <li>"She's a chef happy." <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content">Incorrect word order — the adjective goes first: "She's a <b>happy chef</b>."</div></li>
      <li>"I'm a hard-working nurse." <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content"><b>This sentence is already correct — no error here.</b> The adjective correctly comes before the noun. Resist the urge to change anything.</div></li>
      <li>"Are you a chef and a waiter?" <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content">This should probably be a choice, not an addition: "Are you a chef <b>or</b> a waiter?"</div></li>
      <li>"I'm an artist." <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content"><b>Also correct.</b> "Artist" starts with a vowel sound, so "an" is right. A second trap — not every sentence needs a correction.</div></li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

