    <p><strong>Person A</strong> asks: <em>"What do you do?"</em></p>
    <p><strong>Person B</strong> answers: <em>"I'm a&hellip; / I'm an&hellip;"</em> and one more sentence: <em>"I work in a hospital."</em> Then B asks about A's family: <em>"What does your brother do?"</em> &mdash; <em>"He's an engineer."</em></p>
    <div class="speak-how"><strong>How:</strong> With a partner, or both people yourself. Record 1&ndash;2 minutes. <strong>Check the little word:</strong> <em>a</em> nurse, <em>a</em> teacher &mdash; but <em>an</em> engineer, <em>an</em> artist (before A, E, I, O, U sounds).</div>
  </div>

  <div class="speak-card">
    <span class="speak-type">Sentence challenge</span>
    <h3>Six jobs, one sentence each</h3>
    <p>Say one sentence for each job &mdash; about a real person you know, or a famous person. Up to <strong>60 seconds each</strong>:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><em>a nurse</em></li>
      <li><em>a teacher</em></li>
      <li><em>a driver</em></li>
      <li><em>a chef</em></li>
      <li><em>an engineer</em></li>
      <li><em>an artist</em></li>
    </ul>
    <div class="speak-how"><strong>How:</strong> One recording, timer on. <strong>Check:</strong> <em>"My friend IS a chef. She ISN'T a driver."</em> The verb <em>be</em> is always there!</div>
  </div>

  <div class="speak-card">
    <span class="speak-type">Feelings mirror</span>
    <h3>How are you &mdash; really?</h3>
    <p>Ask yourself aloud: <em>"How are you?"</em> Answer with a feeling word and a face to match: <em>"I'm happy! / I'm tired. / I'm hungry!"</em> Do it five times with five different feelings.</p>
    <div class="speak-how"><strong>How:</strong> In front of the mirror, or record video on your phone. <strong>Check:</strong> the feeling word carries the music &mdash; <em>"I'm TIRED"</em> sounds tired, <em>"I'm HAPPY!"</em> sounds happy.</div>
  </div>

  <div class="tip-box">
    <h3>Tips: jobs and feelings</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Learn YOUR job sentence perfectly: <em>"I'm a&hellip; I work in&hellip;"</em> You will say it a hundred times in your life.</li>
      <li><em>"How are you?"</em> &mdash; <em>"I'm fine, thanks. And you?"</em> Learn the whole ping-pong, not just one side.</li>
