<!-- 1: CONTEXT -->
<!-- SECTION: Context First: Read Before Any Rule -->
<section id="context" class="c1">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">1</span>Context First: Read Before Any Rule</h2>
  <p>Read the conversation about Elena's photo. Just try to understand. We look at the grammar after.</p>

  <div class="realia">
    <span class="doc-tag">Sharing a Photo</span>
    <div class="chat">
      <div class="bubble right"><div class="name">Elena</div>Look, everyone! <span class="highlight">This is</span> a photo of my family.</div>
      <div class="bubble left"><div class="name">Diego</div>Nice! <span class="highlight">Is this</span> your husband?</div>
      <div class="bubble right"><div class="name">Elena</div>Yes, it is. He's <span class="highlight2">tall</span> and <span class="highlight2">young</span>!</div>
      <div class="bubble left"><div class="name">Yuki</div><span class="highlight">Are these</span> your children?</div>
      <div class="bubble right"><div class="name">Elena</div>Yes! <span class="highlight">These are</span> my three children. They're <span class="highlight2">small</span>, but very <span class="highlight2">funny</span>.</div>
      <div class="bubble left"><div class="name">Diego</div>And <span class="highlight">who's that</span>, over there?</div>
      <div class="bubble right"><div class="name">Elena</div><span class="highlight">That's</span> my grandmother. She's <span class="highlight2">old</span>, but very <span class="highlight2">strong</span>!</div>
      <div class="bubble left"><div class="name">Yuki</div>Beautiful family! <span class="highlight">Are you</span> happy in this photo?</div>
      <div class="bubble right"><div class="name">Elena</div>Yes, I am. It was a wonderful day.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p><em>Notice:</em> Elena and her classmates use "this/that/these/those" to point at people in the photo. They also ask questions with "is" and "are", and describe people with words like "tall", "young" and "old".</p>
</section>

<!-- 2: NOTICE -->
<!-- SECTION: Notice the Language (Before Any Rule) -->
<section id="notice" class="c2">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">2</span>Notice the Language (Before Any Rule)</h2>
  <p>You've just read how Diego and Yuki asked Elena about the people in her photo. Before we name any grammar rules, let's look closely at the exact words they used — this will make the rules much easier to understand.</p>
  <p>Look again at the highlighted words. Talk to a partner about these questions.</p>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q1.</b> Find "Is this your husband?" and "Are these your children?" One is about one person, the other about more than one. Which is which?</div>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q2.</b> Elena says "This is a photo" (close, in her hand) but "That's my grandmother" (a person further away in the photo, or in her memory). Do you think "this" and "that" both mean "near"?</div>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q3.</b> Find "Is this...?", "Are these...?" and "Are you...?" Where does "is/are" go in a question — before or after the subject?</div>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q4.</b> Find "tall", "young", "small", "funny", "old", "strong". What job do these words do?</div>
  <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--ink-soft);">Talk about your answers before you go to Section 3.</p>
</section>

<!-- 3: GRAMMAR -->
<!-- SECTION: Grammar Focus -->
<section id="grammar" class="c3">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">3</span>Grammar Focus</h2>
  <p>You noticed that Diego asked "Is this...?" for one person and Yuki asked "Are these...?" for many. Now let's turn those patterns into clear rules you can use to ask about anyone, not just Elena's family.</p>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.1 — To Be: Questions</h3>
  <p>To make a question with "to be", we put am/is/are <b>before</b> the subject.</p>
  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Statement</th><th>Question</th><th>Short answer</th></tr>
    <tr><td>You are Diego.</td><td><b>Are you</b> Diego?</td><td>Yes, I am. / No, I'm not.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>He is your husband.</td><td><b>Is he</b> your husband?</td><td>Yes, he is. / No, he isn't.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>They are your children.</td><td><b>Are they</b> your children?</td><td>Yes, they are. / No, they aren't.</td></tr>
  </table></div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>In a question, does "is/are" go before or after the subject?</b> <span>Before.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>What's the short answer to "Is he tall?" if yes?</b> <span>Yes, he is.</span></div>
  </div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.2 — This / That / These / Those</h3>
  <p>Elena didn't only answer questions — she also pointed at people in the photo herself: "This is a photo of my family," and "That's my grandmother, over there." These words point at people or things. They change depending on distance and number.</p>

  <div class="tl-diagram">
    <div class="tl-diagram-title">Near or far? One or many?</div>
    <svg viewBox="0 0 640 220" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
      <text x="20" y="30" font-size="13" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" font-style="italic">NEAR</text>
      <text x="480" y="30" font-size="13" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" font-style="italic">FAR</text>
      <rect x="20" y="45" width="280" height="75" rx="12" fill="#d9ede7"/>
      <text x="160" y="75" font-size="22" fill="#2e7d6b" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">THIS</text>
      <text x="160" y="100" font-size="13" fill="#26312e" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">one person/thing, near</text>
      <rect x="340" y="45" width="280" height="75" rx="12" fill="#fbe8d3"/>
      <text x="480" y="75" font-size="22" fill="#e08e45" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">THAT</text>
      <text x="480" y="100" font-size="13" fill="#26312e" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">one person/thing, far</text>

      <rect x="20" y="135" width="280" height="75" rx="12" fill="#dcebf5"/>
      <text x="160" y="165" font-size="22" fill="#3e7cb1" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">THESE</text>
      <text x="160" y="190" font-size="13" fill="#26312e" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">many people/things, near</text>
      <rect x="340" y="135" width="280" height="75" rx="12" fill="#f3e1f0"/>
      <text x="480" y="165" font-size="22" fill="#b15fa8" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">THOSE</text>
      <text x="480" y="190" font-size="13" fill="#26312e" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">many people/things, far</text>
    </svg>
    <div class="tl-caption">"This is my husband" (near, one) — "Those are my parents" (far, many)</div>
  </div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Is "this" for one thing or many things?</b> <span>One thing.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Is "those" for near or far?</b> <span>Far.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Which word means "many things, near"?</b> <span>These.</span></div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 4: VOCAB -->
<!-- SECTION: Vocabulary: Describing People -->
<section id="vocab" class="c4">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">4</span>Vocabulary: Describing People</h2>
  <p>Elena described her husband as "tall and young," her children as "small, but very funny," and her grandmother as "old, but very strong." Let's build up your own vocabulary for describing people and their families, just like she did.</p>

  <h3 style="color:var(--plum);">4.1 — Descriptive Adjectives</h3>
  <div class="vocab-grid">
    <div class="vocab-card"><span class="emoji">📏</span><div><b>tall / short</b>height of a person</div></div>
    <div class="vocab-card"><span class="emoji">👶</span><div><b>young / old</b>age of a person</div></div>
    <div class="vocab-card"><span class="emoji">🤏</span><div><b>thin / big</b>body size</div></div>
    <div class="vocab-card"><span class="emoji">😄</span><div><b>funny</b>makes people laugh</div></div>
    <div class="vocab-card"><span class="emoji">💪</span><div><b>strong</b>has a lot of physical power</div></div>
    <div class="vocab-card"><span class="emoji">✨</span><div><b>beautiful / handsome</b>very nice-looking</div></div>
  </div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--plum);">4.2 — Reference List: Family Members</h3>
  <p style="font-size:14px;">Elena mentioned her husband, her children, and her grandmother. Here's a fuller reference list of family words for when you want to describe your own family.</p>
  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Word</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td>mother / father</td><td>a female / male parent</td><td>This is my mother.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>parents</td><td>mother and father together</td><td>These are my parents.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>husband / wife</td><td>a married partner (male / female)</td><td>Is this your husband?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>son / daughter</td><td>a male / female child</td><td>That's my son.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>children</td><td>sons and daughters together</td><td>These are my children.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>brother / sister</td><td>a male / female sibling</td><td>He's my brother.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>grandmother / grandfather</td><td>a parent's mother / father</td><td>That's my grandmother.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>grandson / granddaughter</td><td>a male / female grandchild</td><td>She's my granddaughter.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>aunt / uncle</td><td>a parent's sister / brother</td><td>This is my aunt.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>cousin</td><td>an aunt's or uncle's child</td><td>He's my cousin.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>niece / nephew</td><td>a sibling's daughter / son</td><td>She's my niece.</td></tr>
  </table></div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--plum);">4.3 — Reference List: Adjective Opposites</h3>
  <p style="font-size:14px;">Elena used pairs like "old, but very strong" — knowing opposites helps you describe anyone, quickly. Keep this table as a reference.</p>
  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Adjective</th><th>Opposite</th></tr>
    <tr><td>tall</td><td>short</td></tr>
    <tr><td>young</td><td>old</td></tr>
    <tr><td>big</td><td>small</td></tr>
    <tr><td>thin</td><td>fat</td></tr>
    <tr><td>strong</td><td>weak</td></tr>
    <tr><td>beautiful / handsome</td><td>ugly</td></tr>
    <tr><td>funny</td><td>serious</td></tr>
    <tr><td>happy</td><td>sad</td></tr>
    <tr><td>friendly</td><td>unfriendly</td></tr>
    <tr><td>kind</td><td>unkind</td></tr>
  </table></div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--plum);">4.4 — Numbers (Review): Talking About Age</h3>
  <div class="collo-row">
    <span class="collo-chip">She's 10 years old.</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">He's 35 years old.</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">I'm 20 years old.</span>
  </div>
  <p style="font-size:14px;">Remember your numbers from Week 1! We use them to talk about age: "How old is she?" — "She's <b>ten</b> years old."</p>
</section>

