<!-- 6: ERROR CLINIC -->
<!-- SECTION: Error Clinic -->
<section id="errorclinic" class="c6">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">6</span>Error Clinic</h2>
  <p>Even careful learners mix up "is/are" and "this/these" when they're new to English. Here are five sentences a student might write — read each one. Some have mistakes — fix them. <b>One sentence is already correct — do not "fix" it if it isn't broken.</b></p>
  <div class="box" style="padding:16px 20px;">
    <ol style="font-size:14.5px;">
      <li>"This your husband?" <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content">Incorrect — questions need "is": "<b>Is this</b> your husband?"</div></li>
      <li>"This are my children." <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content">Incorrect — plural, near, needs "these": "<b>These are</b> my children."</div></li>
      <li>"Is he tall?" <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content"><b>This sentence is already correct — no error here.</b> "Is" correctly comes before "he" in the question. Resist the urge to change anything.</div></li>
      <li>"Those is my parents." <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content">Incorrect — plural needs "are": "<b>Those are</b> my parents."</div></li>
      <li>"Are you happy in this photo?" <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content"><b>Also correct.</b> The question word order is right. A second trap — not every sentence needs a correction.</div></li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

