<!-- 1: CONTEXT -->
<!-- SECTION: Context First: Read Before Any Rule -->
<section id="context" class="c1">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">1</span>Context First: Read Before Any Rule</h2>
  <p>Read the conversation about the class schedule. Just try to understand. We look at the grammar after.</p>

  <div class="realia">
    <span class="doc-tag">Class Schedule</span>
    <div class="chat">
      <div class="bubble teacher"><div class="name">Sam</div>OK, everyone! <span class="highlight2">Our</span> class is on Mondays and Wednesdays, at 7 o'clock.</div>
      <div class="bubble right"><div class="name">Elena</div>Great! What about <span class="highlight2">your</span> other classes, Diego?</div>
      <div class="bubble left"><div class="name">Diego</div><span class="highlight2">My</span> work starts at half past eight, every day. It's busy!</div>
      <div class="bubble teacher"><div class="name">Sam</div>OK, open <span class="highlight">your</span> books, everyone! I need two <span class="highlight3">pens</span> and three <span class="highlight3">books</span> for the group table.</div>
      <div class="bubble right"><div class="name">Elena</div>Diego, can you give <span class="highlight3">me</span> a pen, please?</div>
      <div class="bubble left"><div class="name">Diego</div>Sure! Here — this is <span class="highlight2">my</span> pen. I'll give it to <span class="highlight3">you</span> now.</div>
      <div class="bubble teacher"><div class="name">Sam</div>Thanks! And Yuki, can you give <span class="highlight3">them</span> to <span class="highlight3">us</span> — the books on <span class="highlight2">your</span> table?</div>
      <div class="bubble left"><div class="name">Yuki</div>Of course! Here you go.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p><em>Notice:</em> Sam, Elena, Diego and Yuki use "my/your/our" to talk about things that belong to them. Words like "pens" and "books" have an extra "-s" because there's more than one. Small words like "me", "you", "them" and "us" come after verbs.</p>
</section>

<!-- 2: NOTICE -->
<!-- SECTION: Notice the Language (Before Any Rule) -->
<section id="notice" class="c2">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">2</span>Notice the Language (Before Any Rule)</h2>
  <p>You've just read how Sam, Elena, Diego and Yuki talked about their schedule and shared classroom things. Before we name any grammar rules, let's look closely at the exact words they used — this will make the rules much easier to understand.</p>
  <p>Look again at the highlighted words. Talk to a partner about these questions.</p>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q1.</b> Find "pens" and "books". What extra letter do you see at the end? What does this letter tell you?</div>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q2.</b> Find "our class", "my work", "your books". Who does "our" belong to? Who does "my" belong to?</div>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q3.</b> Find "give me a pen", "give it to you", "give them to us". These small words (me, you, them, us) come after the verb "give". Are these the same as "I", "you", "they", "we"?</div>
  <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--ink-soft);">Talk about your answers before you go to Section 3.</p>
</section>

<!-- 3: GRAMMAR -->
<!-- SECTION: Grammar Focus -->
<section id="grammar" class="c3">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">3</span>Grammar Focus</h2>
  <p>You noticed the extra "-s" on "pens" and "books", and that "my/your/our" show who things belong to. Now let's turn those patterns into clear rules you can use with any object, not just Sam's classroom things.</p>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.1 — Plural Nouns</h3>
  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Rule</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Most nouns: + <b>-s</b></td><td>pen → pen<b>s</b>, book → book<b>s</b></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Noun ends in -s, -sh, -ch, -x: + <b>-es</b></td><td>box → box<b>es</b>, watch → watch<b>es</b></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Irregular plurals (no rule, just learn them)</td><td>child → <b>children</b>, man → <b>men</b>, woman → <b>women</b></td></tr>
  </table></div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>What's the plural of "pen"?</b> <span>Pens.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>What's the plural of "child"?</b> <span>Children (irregular).</span></div>
  </div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.1.1 — Reference List: Irregular Plurals</h3>
  <p style="font-size:14px;">Irregular plurals don't follow the "-s" rule, so it's best to learn them as a list. Keep this table as a reference.</p>
  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Singular</th><th>Plural</th></tr>
    <tr><td>man</td><td>men</td></tr>
    <tr><td>woman</td><td>women</td></tr>
    <tr><td>child</td><td>children</td></tr>
    <tr><td>person</td><td>people</td></tr>
    <tr><td>tooth</td><td>teeth</td></tr>
    <tr><td>foot</td><td>feet</td></tr>
    <tr><td>mouse</td><td>mice</td></tr>
    <tr><td>goose</td><td>geese</td></tr>
    <tr><td>fish</td><td>fish (no change)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>sheep</td><td>sheep (no change)</td></tr>
  </table></div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.2 — Possessive Adjectives</h3>
  <p>Sam said "<b>our</b> class," Elena asked about "<b>your</b> other classes," and Diego talked about "<b>my</b> work." These small words show who something belongs to.</p>
  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Subject</th><th>Possessive adjective</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td>I</td><td><b>my</b></td><td><b>My</b> pen is blue.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>you</td><td><b>your</b></td><td>Is this <b>your</b> book?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>he</td><td><b>his</b></td><td>This is <b>his</b> bag.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>she</td><td><b>her</b></td><td>That's <b>her</b> pen.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>it</td><td><b>its</b></td><td>The class has <b>its</b> own room.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>we</td><td><b>our</b></td><td><b>Our</b> class is on Monday.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>they</td><td><b>their</b></td><td>These are <b>their</b> books.</td></tr>
  </table></div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Which word means "belongs to me"?</b> <span>My.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Which word means "belongs to us"?</b> <span>Our.</span></div>
  </div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.3 — Object Pronouns</h3>
  <p>Elena asked Diego to "give <b>me</b> a pen," and Sam asked Yuki to "give <b>them</b> to <b>us</b>." Object pronouns come <b>after</b> a verb (like "give", "help", "call").</p>
  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Subject pronoun</th><th>Object pronoun</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td>I</td><td><b>me</b></td><td>Give it to <b>me</b>.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>you</td><td><b>you</b></td><td>I'll give it to <b>you</b>.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>he</td><td><b>him</b></td><td>Call <b>him</b>, please.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>she</td><td><b>her</b></td><td>Help <b>her</b>, please.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>we</td><td><b>us</b></td><td>Give them to <b>us</b>.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>they</td><td><b>them</b></td><td>Give <b>them</b> to Yuki.</td></tr>
  </table></div>

  <div class="error-box">
    <h4>⚠️ Don't Confuse Subject and Object!</h4>
    <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
      <tr><th>❌ Incorrect</th><th>✅ Correct</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Give it to I.</td><td>Give it to <b>me</b>.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Call he, please.</td><td>Call <b>him</b>, please.</td></tr>
    </table></div>
  </div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Do we say "give it to I" or "give it to me"?</b> <span>Give it to me.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>What's the object pronoun for "he"?</b> <span>Him.</span></div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 4: TIME -->
<!-- SECTION: Telling the Time -->
<section id="time" class="c4">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">4</span>Telling the Time</h2>
  <p>Remember how Sam said "our class is on Mondays and Wednesdays, at <b>7 o'clock</b>," and Diego said his work starts "at <b>half past eight</b>"? Let's look closely at exactly how to say and understand times like these — and a few more useful ones too.</p>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">4.1 — The Four Key Times</h3>
  <p style="font-size:14px;">Every hour has four important "landmark" times. Once you know these four, you can build almost any time.</p>
  <div class="tl-diagram">
    <div class="tl-diagram-title">O'clock, quarter past, half past, quarter to</div>
    <svg viewBox="0 0 500 460" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
      <!-- Clock 1: 3 o'clock -->
      <circle cx="130" cy="100" r="70" fill="#fffefb" stroke="#2e7d6b" stroke-width="4"/>
      <text x="130" y="42" font-size="14" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">12</text>
      <text x="192" y="106" font-size="14" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">3</text>
      <text x="130" y="176" font-size="14" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">6</text>
      <text x="68" y="106" font-size="14" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">9</text>
      <line x1="130" y1="100" x2="130" y2="65" stroke="#2e7d6b" stroke-width="4" stroke-linecap="round" transform="rotate(90,130,100)"/>
      <line x1="130" y1="100" x2="130" y2="50" stroke="#2e7d6b" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" transform="rotate(0,130,100)"/>
      <circle cx="130" cy="100" r="4" fill="#2e7d6b"/>
      <text x="130" y="195" font-size="15" fill="#26312e" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">3 o'clock</text>
      <text x="130" y="213" font-size="12" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">(3:00)</text>

      <!-- Clock 2: quarter past 3 -->
      <circle cx="370" cy="100" r="70" fill="#fffefb" stroke="#e08e45" stroke-width="4"/>
      <text x="370" y="42" font-size="14" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">12</text>
      <text x="432" y="106" font-size="14" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">3</text>
      <text x="370" y="176" font-size="14" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">6</text>
      <text x="308" y="106" font-size="14" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">9</text>
      <line x1="370" y1="100" x2="370" y2="65" stroke="#e08e45" stroke-width="4" stroke-linecap="round" transform="rotate(97.5,370,100)"/>
      <line x1="370" y1="100" x2="370" y2="45" stroke="#e08e45" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" transform="rotate(90,370,100)"/>
      <circle cx="370" cy="100" r="4" fill="#e08e45"/>
      <text x="370" y="195" font-size="15" fill="#26312e" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">quarter past 3</text>
      <text x="370" y="213" font-size="12" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">(3:15)</text>

      <!-- Clock 3: half past 3 -->
      <circle cx="130" cy="340" r="70" fill="#fffefb" stroke="#3e7cb1" stroke-width="4"/>
      <text x="130" y="282" font-size="14" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">12</text>
      <text x="192" y="346" font-size="14" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">3</text>
      <text x="130" y="416" font-size="14" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">6</text>
      <text x="68" y="346" font-size="14" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">9</text>
      <line x1="130" y1="340" x2="130" y2="305" stroke="#3e7cb1" stroke-width="4" stroke-linecap="round" transform="rotate(105,130,340)"/>
      <line x1="130" y1="340" x2="130" y2="285" stroke="#3e7cb1" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" transform="rotate(180,130,340)"/>
      <circle cx="130" cy="340" r="4" fill="#3e7cb1"/>
      <text x="130" y="435" font-size="15" fill="#26312e" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">half past 3</text>
      <text x="130" y="453" font-size="12" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">(3:30)</text>

      <!-- Clock 4: quarter to 4 -->
      <circle cx="370" cy="340" r="70" fill="#fffefb" stroke="#b15fa8" stroke-width="4"/>
      <text x="370" y="282" font-size="14" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">12</text>
      <text x="432" y="346" font-size="14" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">3</text>
      <text x="370" y="416" font-size="14" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">6</text>
      <text x="308" y="346" font-size="14" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">9</text>
      <line x1="370" y1="340" x2="370" y2="305" stroke="#b15fa8" stroke-width="4" stroke-linecap="round" transform="rotate(112.5,370,340)"/>
      <line x1="370" y1="340" x2="370" y2="285" stroke="#b15fa8" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round" transform="rotate(270,370,340)"/>
      <circle cx="370" cy="340" r="4" fill="#b15fa8"/>
      <text x="370" y="435" font-size="15" fill="#26312e" font-family="Calibri" font-weight="bold" text-anchor="middle">quarter to 4</text>
      <text x="370" y="453" font-size="12" fill="#5a6863" font-family="Calibri" text-anchor="middle">(3:45)</text>
    </svg>
    <div class="tl-caption">Notice: after half past, we start counting down to the <em>next</em> hour — "quarter to 4", not "quarter past half".</div>
  </div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>"Quarter" means how many minutes?</b> <span>15 minutes.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Is 3:45 called "quarter to 4" or "quarter to 3"?</b> <span>Quarter to 4 — we look forward to the next hour.</span></div>
  </div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">4.2 — Reference List: Minutes Past &amp; To</h3>
  <p style="font-size:14px;">For times that aren't o'clock, quarter, or half, we use "past" (after the hour) or "to" (before the next hour). Keep this table as a reference.</p>
  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Time</th><th>We say</th></tr>
    <tr><td>3:05</td><td><b>five past</b> 3</td></tr>
    <tr><td>3:10</td><td><b>ten past</b> 3</td></tr>
    <tr><td>3:15</td><td><b>quarter past</b> 3</td></tr>
    <tr><td>3:20</td><td><b>twenty past</b> 3</td></tr>
    <tr><td>3:25</td><td><b>twenty-five past</b> 3</td></tr>
    <tr><td>3:30</td><td><b>half past</b> 3</td></tr>
    <tr><td>3:35</td><td><b>twenty-five to</b> 4</td></tr>
    <tr><td>3:40</td><td><b>twenty to</b> 4</td></tr>
    <tr><td>3:45</td><td><b>quarter to</b> 4</td></tr>
    <tr><td>3:50</td><td><b>ten to</b> 4</td></tr>
    <tr><td>3:55</td><td><b>five to</b> 4</td></tr>
  </table></div>
  <p style="font-size:14px;"><em>Tip: up to and including 30 minutes, we count "past" the hour. After 30 minutes, we count "to" the next hour.</em></p>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">4.3 — Asking and Answering</h3>
  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Question</th><th>Answer</th></tr>
    <tr><td>What time is it?</td><td>It's <b>quarter past 3</b>.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>What time does the class start?</td><td>It starts at <b>7 o'clock</b>.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>What time does it finish?</td><td>It finishes at <b>half past 5</b>.</td></tr>
  </table></div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Do we say "It's" or "It has" before a time?</b> <span>It's (It is).</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Do we say "at 7 o'clock" or "in 7 o'clock"?</b> <span>At 7 o'clock.</span></div>
  </div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">4.4 — Morning, Afternoon, Evening, Night</h3>
  <p style="font-size:14px;">English usually doesn't use 13:00, 14:00, etc. in speech — instead, we add a part of the day.</p>
  <div class="collo-row">
    <span class="collo-chip">🌅 morning (before 12pm)</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">☀️ afternoon (12pm–6pm)</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">🌆 evening (6pm–bedtime)</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">🌙 night (bedtime–early morning)</span>
  </div>
  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>24-hour</th><th>We say</th></tr>
    <tr><td>7:00</td><td>7 o'clock in the morning</td></tr>
    <tr><td>14:30</td><td>half past 2 in the afternoon</td></tr>
    <tr><td>19:15</td><td>quarter past 7 in the evening</td></tr>
    <tr><td>23:00</td><td>11 o'clock at night</td></tr>
  </table></div>
  <p style="font-size:14px;"><em>Note: with "night" we say "<b>at</b> night", not "in the night".</em></p>
</section>

<!-- 5: VOCAB -->
<!-- SECTION: Vocabulary: Days & Months -->
<section id="vocab" class="c5">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">5</span>Vocabulary: Days &amp; Months</h2>
  <p>Sam mentioned "Mondays and Wednesdays" — knowing all the days and months lets you talk about your own schedule, just like Sam, Elena and Diego did. Let's also add more classroom objects to the pens and books you already know.</p>

  <h3 style="color:var(--plum);">5.1 — Days of the Week</h3>
  <div class="collo-row">
    <span class="collo-chip">Monday</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">Tuesday</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">Wednesday</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">Thursday</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">Friday</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">Saturday</span>
    <span class="collo-chip">Sunday</span>
  </div>

