  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">7</span>Error Clinic</h2>
  <p>Even careful learners mix up plurals and object pronouns when they're new to English. Here are five sentences a student might write — read each one. Some have mistakes — fix them. <b>One sentence is already correct — do not "fix" it if it isn't broken.</b></p>
  <div class="box" style="padding:16px 20px;">
    <ol style="font-size:14.5px;">
      <li>"Give it to I." <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content">Incorrect — after a verb, use the object pronoun: "Give it to <b>me</b>."</div></li>
      <li>"I need two pen." <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content">Incorrect — "two" needs a plural noun: "I need two <b>pens</b>."</div></li>
      <li>"This is my pen." <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content"><b>This sentence is already correct — no error here.</b> "My" correctly shows it belongs to "I". Resist the urge to change anything.</div></li>
      <li>"Call he, please." <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content">Incorrect — use the object pronoun: "Call <b>him</b>, please."</div></li>
      <li>"Our class is on Monday." <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content"><b>Also correct.</b> "Our" and the capital letter on "Monday" are both correct. A second trap — not every sentence needs a correction.</div></li>
