<!-- 2: NOTICE -->
<!-- SECTION: Notice the Language (Before Any Rule) -->
<section id="notice" class="c2">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">2</span>Notice the Language (Before Any Rule)</h2>
  <p>You've just read how the class planned — and celebrated — their goodbye party. Before we name any grammar rules, let's look closely at the exact words they used — this will make the rules much easier to understand.</p>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q1.</b> Find "What shall we bring?", "Where shall we have the party?", "When does everyone finish?", "Who else is coming?", "Why don't we start at half past six?" and "How many people is that?" Each question starts with a different question word. What kind of answer does each one need (a place, a time, a person, a reason, a number)?</div>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q2.</b> Find "Can I have some cake, please?" and "Can you pass the drinks, please?" Who is asking for something for themselves? Who is asking someone else to do something?</div>
  <div class="notice-q"><b>Q3.</b> Find every greeting and farewell in the party conversation (hi, hello, good evening, nice to meet you, goodbye, take care, see you soon, bye). Which ones do we say at the start of a conversation? Which ones do we say at the end?</div>
  <p style="font-size:14px;color:var(--ink-soft);">Talk about your answers before you go to Section 3.</p>
</section>

<!-- 3: GRAMMAR -->
<!-- SECTION: Grammar Focus -->
<section id="grammar" class="c3">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">3</span>Grammar Focus</h2>
  <p>You noticed that each question word — what, where, when, who, why, how — asks for a different kind of answer, and that "can" changes meaning depending on who it's for. Now let's turn those patterns into clear rules you can use in any conversation.</p>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.1 — Wh- Questions</h3>
  <p>Question words go at the <b>very start</b> of a question, before the verb.</p>

  <div class="wh-grid">
    <div class="wh-card" style="border-color:var(--green);"><div class="word" style="color:var(--green);">What</div><div class="meaning">a thing</div><div class="example">What's your name?</div></div>
    <div class="wh-card" style="border-color:var(--orange);"><div class="word" style="color:var(--orange);">Where</div><div class="meaning">a place</div><div class="example">Where do you live?</div></div>
    <div class="wh-card" style="border-color:var(--blue);"><div class="word" style="color:var(--blue);">When</div><div class="meaning">a time</div><div class="example">When is the party?</div></div>
    <div class="wh-card" style="border-color:var(--plum);"><div class="word" style="color:var(--plum);">Who</div><div class="meaning">a person</div><div class="example">Who is coming?</div></div>
    <div class="wh-card" style="border-color:var(--gold);"><div class="word" style="color:var(--gold);">Why</div><div class="meaning">a reason</div><div class="example">Why are you late?</div></div>
    <div class="wh-card" style="border-color:var(--green);"><div class="word" style="color:var(--green);">How</div><div class="meaning">a way/manner</div><div class="example">How are you?</div></div>
  </div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Which question word asks about a place?</b> <span>Where.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Which question word asks about a person?</b> <span>Who.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Does the question word go at the start or end of a question?</b> <span>Start.</span></div>
  </div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.1.1 — Reference List: Question Words</h3>
  <p style="font-size:14px;">Here is a fuller reference list of question words, including some useful combinations with "how".</p>
  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Word</th><th>Asks about</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td>What</td><td>a thing</td><td>What's this?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Where</td><td>a place</td><td>Where's the party?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>When</td><td>a time</td><td>When does it start?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Who</td><td>a person</td><td>Who's coming?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Whose</td><td>an owner</td><td>Whose cake is this?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Why</td><td>a reason</td><td>Why are you happy?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>How</td><td>a way/manner</td><td>How are you?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>How much</td><td>a price/amount (uncountable)</td><td>How much is the cake?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>How many</td><td>a number (countable)</td><td>How many people are coming?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>How old</td><td>an age</td><td>How old are you?</td></tr>
  </table></div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--blue);">3.2 — Can for Requests</h3>
  <p>Diego asked "Can I have some cake?" for himself, and Sam asked "Can you pass the drinks?" to ask Yuki to do something. Same word, two different jobs.</p>

  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Use</th><th>Form</th><th>Example</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Asking for something for yourself</td><td><b>Can I</b> + verb...?</td><td><b>Can I have</b> some cake, please?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Asking someone else to do something</td><td><b>Can you</b> + verb...?</td><td><b>Can you pass</b> the drinks, please?</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Positive reply</td><td>Sure! / Of course! / Yes, here you go.</td><td>—</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Polite negative reply</td><td>Sorry, I can't. / I'm afraid not.</td><td>—</td></tr>
  </table></div>

  <div class="error-box">
    <h4>⚠️ Don't Forget "Please"!</h4>
    <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
      <tr><th>❌ Less Polite</th><th>✅ More Polite</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Can I have cake.</td><td>Can I have some cake, <b>please</b>?</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Can you pass the drinks.</td><td>Can you pass the drinks, <b>please</b>?</td></tr>
    </table></div>
  </div>

  <div class="ccq-box">
    <h4>🔎 Check Your Understanding</h4>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Do we say "Can I" or "Can you" when we want something for ourselves?</b> <span>Can I.</span></div>
    <div class="ccq-item"><b>Do we say "Can I" or "Can you" when we ask someone else to do something?</b> <span>Can you.</span></div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 4: VOCAB -->
<!-- SECTION: Vocabulary: Greetings -->
<section id="vocab" class="c4">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">4</span>Vocabulary: Greetings</h2>
  <p>The party conversation was full of greetings and farewells — "Hi", "Hello", "Good evening", "Nice to meet you", "Goodbye", "Take care", "See you soon", "Bye". Let's organise them so you always know what to say, and when.</p>

  <h3 style="color:var(--plum);">4.1 — Starting a Conversation</h3>
  <div class="vocab-grid">
    <div class="vocab-card"><span class="emoji">👋</span><div><b>Hi / Hello</b>casual and friendly, any time</div></div>
    <div class="vocab-card"><span class="emoji">🌅</span><div><b>Good morning</b>before 12pm</div></div>
    <div class="vocab-card"><span class="emoji">☀️</span><div><b>Good afternoon</b>12pm–6pm</div></div>
    <div class="vocab-card"><span class="emoji">🌆</span><div><b>Good evening</b>after 6pm</div></div>
    <div class="vocab-card"><span class="emoji">🤝</span><div><b>Nice to meet you</b>the first time you meet someone</div></div>
    <div class="vocab-card"><span class="emoji">😊</span><div><b>How are you?</b>asking about someone's wellbeing</div></div>
  </div>

  <h3 style="color:var(--plum);">4.2 — Ending a Conversation</h3>
  <div class="vocab-grid">
    <div class="vocab-card"><span class="emoji">👋</span><div><b>Goodbye / Bye</b>the standard way to leave</div></div>
    <div class="vocab-card"><span class="emoji">💚</span><div><b>Take care</b>a warm, friendly goodbye</div></div>
    <div class="vocab-card"><span class="emoji">🔜</span><div><b>See you soon / later</b>you'll meet again soon</div></div>
    <div class="vocab-card"><span class="emoji">🌙</span><div><b>Good night</b>only when someone is going to bed</div></div>
  </div>
  <p style="font-size:14px;"><em>Note: "Good night" is a farewell (for bedtime), but "Good morning/afternoon/evening" are greetings (for hello)!</em></p>

  <h3 style="color:var(--plum);">4.3 — Reference List: Useful Party Phrases</h3>
  <div class="table-scroll"><table class="rules">
    <tr><th>Phrase</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
    <tr><td>Here you go.</td><td>said when giving something to someone</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Sure! / No problem!</td><td>a friendly "yes" to a request</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Thank you (so much).</td><td>expressing gratitude</td></tr>
    <tr><td>You're welcome.</td><td>a reply to "thank you"</td></tr>
    <tr><td>It was nice to meet you.</td><td>said when leaving, after meeting someone new</td></tr>
  </table></div>
</section>

