<!-- 6: ERROR CLINIC -->
<!-- SECTION: Error Clinic -->
<section id="errorclinic" class="c6">
  <h2 class="sec-title"><span class="tab-num">6</span>Error Clinic</h2>
  <p>Even careful learners mix up question words and "can I/you" when they're new to English. Here are five sentences a student might write — read each one. Some have mistakes — fix them. <b>One sentence is already correct — do not "fix" it if it isn't broken.</b></p>
  <div class="box" style="padding:16px 20px;">
    <ol style="font-size:14.5px;">
      <li>"Who is the party?" <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content">Incorrect — asking about a place needs "where": "<b>Where</b> is the party?"</div></li>
      <li>"Can you have some cake, please?" (asking for yourself) <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content">Incorrect — asking for yourself needs "Can I": "<b>Can I</b> have some cake, please?"</div></li>
      <li>"Can you pass the drinks, please?" <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content"><b>This sentence is already correct — no error here.</b> Asking someone else to do something correctly uses "Can you". Resist the urge to change anything.</div></li>
      <li>"What time the party start?" <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content">Incorrect — missing "does": "What time <b>does</b> the party start?"</div></li>
      <li>"Good night! Nice to meet you at the party!" (said when arriving) <button class="reveal-btn" onclick="this.nextElementSibling.style.display='block'">Reveal</button><div class="reveal-content">Incorrect greeting — "good night" is only for bedtime: "<b>Good evening!</b> Nice to meet you at the party!"</div></li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

